{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567710"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19272"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19272"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.08,0.32,0.27,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82485"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12006"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67648"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3871"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"8824"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39582"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82485"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with gradually worsening vision in both eyes over the past eight months. She has no eye pain or redness. She has hypermetropia, diabetes, hypertension and takes perindopril and metformin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/18 in the right eye and 6/12 in the left eye with her glasses. Gonioscopy reveals peripheral anterior synechiae in both eyes. The optic discs show bilateral cupping with a cup-to-disc ratio of 0.7 in both eyes.  Her eye pressures were also to be measured.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systemic acetazolamide","YAG laser capsulotomy","Laser peripheral iridotomy","Topical prostaglandin analogues","Topical beta-blockers"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features commonly seen in chronic angle-closure glaucoma (CACG). Patients commonly present with no pain and slow vision loss and on examination, there may be peripheral anterior synechiae on gonioscopy due to the chronicity of the disease. The presence of hypermetropia is a risk factor as these patients typically have smaller anterior chambers. Risk factors for chronic angle-closure glaucoma include being over the fifth decade of life, Asian or Inuit heritage, female, having small eyes, and a family history of glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser peripheral iridotomy\u003C/strong\u003E (LPI) is the definitive treatment for CACG. Iridotomy involved equalising pressure between the chambers (anterior and posterior) through a small hole in the peripheral iris. This also works to prevent further angle closure. This procedure should be performed before starting medical therapy to address the underlying anatomical problem. Iridoplasty is second-line treatment if required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical beta-blockers\u003C/strong\u003E such as timolol can lower intraocular pressure by reducing aqueous production. However, they do not address the underlying anatomical problem of angle closure and should not be used as first-line therapy without LPI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic acetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for acute angle-closure glaucoma with very high pressures requiring urgent pressure reduction. It is not appropriate as first-line therapy for chronic cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYAG laser capsulotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat posterior capsular opacification after cataract surgery. It has no role in the management of angle-closure glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical prostaglandin analogues\u003C/strong\u003E like latanoprost increase uveoscleral outflow to lower intraocular pressure. While they may be used as adjunctive therapy after LPI, they are not the most appropriate first step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter LPI, medical therapy with pressure-lowering drops may still be required if the intraocular pressure remains elevated. Regular monitoring of intraocular pressure, visual fields, and optic disc appearance is essential to track disease progression. Patients at risk of glaucoma should have regular eye reviews for early detection as most early cases are asymptomatic thus are often missed. Severe complications of glaucoma include irreversible blindness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic angle-closure glaucoma typically presents with gradual, painless vision loss and elevated intraocular pressure.","Gonioscopy showing peripheral anterior synechiae is diagnostic for chronic angle-closure glaucoma.","Laser peripheral iridotomy is the definitive treatment for chronic angle-closure glaucoma to prevent further progression."],"references":["Tham C, Kwong Y, Lai J, Lam D, Ritch R. Surgical management of chronic angle-closure glaucoma. Expert Review of Ophthalmology. 2007: 2(2).  Available at: https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1586/17469899.2.2.185","Wormald RPL, Jones E. Glaucoma: acute and chronic primary angle-closure. BMJ Clin Evid. 2015.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4673911/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67648"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19272"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67648"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T19:11:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T19:13:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12006"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82485"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"cr